WEBVTT

00:01.359 --> 00:03.890
<i>Nationals is in New York City,</i>
<i>and everyone's really excited.</i>

00:03.900 --> 00:05.210
<i>Jessie St. James</i>
<i>is back in town,</i>

00:05.210 --> 00:06.960
<i>and he's starting a show choir</i>
<i>consulting business.</i>

00:07.000 --> 00:08.130
Two things that I'm great at...

00:08.220 --> 00:09.930
Show choir and destroying the competition.

00:09.950 --> 00:10.850
<i>The New Directions!</i>
<i>Should hire him.</i>

00:10.890 --> 00:13.210
<i>A.) They really want to win</i>
<i>and B.) He's super-handsome.</i>

00:13.250 --> 00:15.260
<i>Terri's back, too,</i>
<i>and Sue wants the Honey Badger</i>

00:15.260 --> 00:15.280
<i>to take out the Glee Club</i> <i>Terri's back,
too,</i> <i>and Sue wants the Honey Badger</i>

00:15.280 --> 00:15.910
<i>to take out the Glee Club</i>

00:15.960 --> 00:17.230
<i>before they can get</i>
<i>to New York.</i>

00:17.250 --> 00:19.060
<i>And that's what</i>
<i>you missed on</i> Glee.

00:19.260 --> 00:20.259
Sync by Thanh Hoang
www.Itfriend.ORG
www.Addic7ed.com

00:20.260 --> 00:22.080
New Directions!,
I would like to introduce you

00:22.130 --> 00:24.270
to our new show choir consultant...

00:24.350 --> 00:26.970
Jessie St. James.

00:27.050 --> 00:29.220
I don't trust this guy.

00:29.270 --> 00:30.690
How do we know he's not
just going to trick us

00:30.760 --> 00:32.560
into doing something stupid,
so his Alma mater wins?

00:32.610 --> 00:33.980
I don't think I need to do much tricking

00:34.060 --> 00:35.280
to get you to do something stupid, Finn.

00:35.360 --> 00:37.260
Guys, Jessie is just a consultant.

00:37.310 --> 00:39.310
I still make all the calls.

00:39.400 --> 00:41.680
Now, I have all the confidence
in the world in you guys.

00:41.750 --> 00:43.920
I just think we could use
all the help we can get.

00:43.990 --> 00:46.050
Because...

00:46.120 --> 00:47.290
This is it.

00:47.360 --> 00:49.060
We've been working so hard for two years

00:49.120 --> 00:51.580
for this moment, and that
moment is finally here.

00:51.630 --> 00:53.530
Now, I was talking with
Jessie, and he agreed

00:53.600 --> 00:55.300
that we should continue
with our successful trend

00:55.360 --> 00:57.400
of doing original songs
for the competition.

00:57.470 --> 00:59.580
I was thinking of doing one group number

00:59.640 --> 01:01.720
and one duet.
Rachel and I should sing a duet.

01:01.790 --> 01:03.440
We killed it last year
at Regionals with "Faithfully."

01:03.510 --> 01:05.770
Yeah, killed us...
we lost.

01:05.840 --> 01:07.020
May I?
Uh, yeah.

01:07.090 --> 01:09.590
I agree that Rachel should sing lead,

01:09.660 --> 01:12.010
but Finn, I think it's best
if you sit this one out.

01:12.100 --> 01:14.600
Fact is, most of the other guys
in here are better singers,

01:14.650 --> 01:17.540
and Mike Chang, who can't
even sing, can at least dance.

01:17.600 --> 01:20.100
You kind of sing and dance
like a zombie who has to poop.

01:20.160 --> 01:21.270
You-you see? You see
what I'm talking about?

01:21.320 --> 01:22.670
The guy's a jerk!

01:22.740 --> 01:25.010
Jessie, maybe you could, uh,
be a little bit gentler

01:25.080 --> 01:26.490
with your advice.
Gentle?

01:26.560 --> 01:28.200
Yes.
I'm sorry.

01:28.260 --> 01:29.650
I didn't realize that we were training

01:29.720 --> 01:31.050
for the "good try" ribbon at Nationals.

01:31.120 --> 01:33.450
I thought we were in it
to win the whole damn thing.

01:33.520 --> 01:34.890
And there's only one way we can do that.

01:34.950 --> 01:36.220
Poison darts?

01:36.290 --> 01:37.890
The Vocal Adrenaline strategy is simple...

01:37.960 --> 01:39.960
Identify your best performer

01:40.030 --> 01:42.330
and build the entire performance
around them.

01:42.390 --> 01:44.060
So what does everyone else do?

01:44.130 --> 01:45.400
And who's our star performer?

01:46.850 --> 01:48.470
We're going to have auditions to find out.

01:48.520 --> 01:50.500
I'm going to post
a sign-up sheet

01:50.570 --> 01:51.850
later this afternoon.
Mr. Shue,

01:51.940 --> 01:53.940
don't you think this
is kind of not our style?

01:54.010 --> 01:56.620
Normally, I'd agree with you,
Finn, but this is the big time.

01:56.690 --> 01:57.890
I think we should listen to Jessie.

02:05.480 --> 02:07.350
I just don't know what
you're so angry about.

02:07.400 --> 02:09.639
Honey Badger, I am lactating with rage!

02:09.710 --> 02:11.110
The Glee Club travels

02:11.170 --> 02:13.690
to New York for Nationals in one week.

02:13.740 --> 02:15.380
They have purchased airline tickets...

02:15.460 --> 02:17.360
Tickets that I would like to screw up.

02:17.430 --> 02:19.880
I asked you to recruit
an expert computer hacker,

02:19.970 --> 02:21.830
and you bring me this.

02:23.020 --> 02:24.670
Do I get a super villain nickname?

02:24.740 --> 02:26.000
Your nickname is Panda Express.

02:26.070 --> 02:28.120
But I'm not Chinese.

02:28.190 --> 02:29.670
Neither is the food at Panda Express.

02:29.730 --> 02:30.990
Look, I'm on top of this.

02:31.060 --> 02:32.460
All the official travel for the school

02:32.530 --> 02:34.060
goes through
the Lima Heights Travel Agency.

02:34.130 --> 02:36.130
All we have to do is e-mail them

02:36.200 --> 02:38.300
through Principal Figgins'
e-mail account.

02:38.370 --> 02:40.270
So what's the hold up?
We don't know his password.

02:40.350 --> 02:41.740
Principal Figgins is an idiot...

02:41.820 --> 02:43.340
Something America is chock full of.

02:43.410 --> 02:47.310
What is the most common password
in America?

02:47.380 --> 02:49.280
One, two, three, four?

02:51.630 --> 02:52.560
We're in.
Outstanding.

02:54.170 --> 02:56.250
The travel agency sent arday

02:56.340 --> 02:58.840
confirming an itinerary
with a layover in Chicago

02:58.890 --> 03:00.420
before heading on to New York.

03:00.510 --> 03:02.340
Compose an e-mail
requesting a flight

03:02.390 --> 03:04.890
that's routed through Tripoli.

03:04.980 --> 03:06.380
Tripoli?
Wait, isn't that in Libya?

03:06.430 --> 03:08.550
The second that plane touches the tarmac,

03:08.600 --> 03:10.380
they'll be swarmed by armed militants.

03:10.430 --> 03:12.770
Wait, are-are we trying
to have the Glee Club killed?

03:12.850 --> 03:14.050
Or kidnapped and killed.

03:15.550 --> 03:18.390
Panda... make it so.

03:18.440 --> 03:20.530
Someone really woke up on the
wrong side of the bed today.

03:20.580 --> 03:22.990
You have no idea.

03:24.700 --> 03:25.900
Mr. Schuester?

03:25.950 --> 03:27.080
Oh, hey, Becky.

03:27.170 --> 03:28.200
Mr. Schuester,
I'm Donna Jackson.

03:28.250 --> 03:29.500
I'm Becky's mom.

03:29.570 --> 03:32.250
I really need to talk to you.

03:32.340 --> 03:34.290
I want to be in Glee Club.

03:34.360 --> 03:37.170
Well, that's great, Becky.
Can you sing?

03:37.240 --> 03:41.510
Not really, but neither can most
of the kids in Glee Club.

03:41.580 --> 03:42.760
But I-I thought
you were having

03:42.850 --> 03:44.050
such a good time on the Cheerios!

03:44.100 --> 03:45.330
Sue kicked her off.

03:47.250 --> 03:49.100
Becky, you're off the Cheerios!

03:49.190 --> 03:51.560
I don't want to see you anymore.
Is that understood?

03:52.720 --> 03:54.690
Did I do something wrong, Coach?

03:54.760 --> 03:56.230
You heard what I said.

03:56.280 --> 03:59.250
I want your pom-poms on my desk
by the end of the day.

04:01.430 --> 04:04.490
I... I-I don't know what to say.

04:04.570 --> 04:06.020
Becky's been totally depressed.

04:06.090 --> 04:07.770
She hasn't been eating...

04:07.820 --> 04:10.630
Can I please be
in Glee Club, Mr. Shue?

04:10.710 --> 04:12.580
I just want to belong.

04:14.130 --> 04:16.829
Becky...

04:16.920 --> 04:18.950
We're a week away from Nationals.

04:19.000 --> 04:22.550
I mean... I mean, the...
the season is almost over.

04:22.620 --> 04:25.510
I'd love for you to join next year.

04:25.590 --> 04:27.780
But for now, I...

04:27.840 --> 04:30.340
I'm afraid there just
isn't a place for you.

04:30.430 --> 04:32.960
We understand.

04:33.020 --> 04:34.380
Thank you for your time.

04:34.450 --> 04:35.730
Yeah.

04:35.800 --> 04:38.400
I hate this school.

04:39.940 --> 04:40.940
You are a terrible person.

04:40.990 --> 04:42.660
Becky was loyal to you, Sue.

04:42.740 --> 04:44.110
Cheerios! Gave her
a sense of purpose,

04:44.160 --> 04:45.910
and then you just rip it away
from her for no reason.

04:45.980 --> 04:47.650
I'm going to be honest with you, Will.

04:47.700 --> 04:48.780
I do have a reason.

04:48.830 --> 04:50.620
She reminds me of my sister.

04:50.670 --> 04:52.080
What does that have to do with anything?

04:52.150 --> 04:53.420
You love your sister.

04:53.490 --> 04:56.290
I do, William, and she died yesterday.

04:59.310 --> 05:00.570
What?

05:02.440 --> 05:04.500
You know, when we were younger,
people always told me

05:04.550 --> 05:06.280
Jean wouldn't live very long.

05:06.350 --> 05:10.020
Used to be that people
with Down's didn't live past 30.

05:10.100 --> 05:14.170
But then she turned 35, and then 40,

05:14.220 --> 05:17.120
and when she turned 50, I thought, somehow,

05:17.190 --> 05:19.510
we might grow old together.

05:20.950 --> 05:22.680
Last week, she got pneumonia.

05:22.730 --> 05:25.530
Doctor said it wasn't bad,
and they put her on antibiotics.

05:28.950 --> 05:31.210
I was there with her.

05:31.290 --> 05:33.660
I wanted to stay the night,

05:33.710 --> 05:36.540
and she told me to go home.

05:36.630 --> 05:38.910
At 2:00 A.M., I got the call

05:39.000 --> 05:41.480
that she had passed away in her sleep.

05:41.550 --> 05:44.500
Sue, I am so sorry.

05:44.550 --> 05:46.800
Could you leave me alone, please?

